🧭 The Framing Compass (practical version)

Instead of “control,” think:

align → nudge → check → adjust

⸻

⚙️ The Core Moves (your “cane,” but grounded)

1. Anchor the shared reality

Start where both sides agree.
	•	“Right now we’re dealing with…”
	•	“What we both want is…”

👉 This reduces resistance immediately.

⸻

2. Open the possibility space

Don’t lock the outcome—expand options.
	•	“There are a couple ways this could go…”
	•	“We could look at it like…”

👉 Keeps the other person engaged instead of defensive.

⸻

3. Bias the direction (subtle but clear)

Now introduce your preferred trajectory.
	•	“The version that seems to solve most of this is…”
	•	“The cleaner path might be…”

👉 You’re guiding, not forcing.

⸻

4. Invite alignment (not compliance)

Let them step into it.
	•	“Does that track with you?”
	•	“How does that land?”

👉 This is where buy-in happens.

⸻

5. Adjust based on feedback

If they resist, you don’t push—you reframe.
	•	“Okay, let’s look at it another way…”
	•	“What would need to be true for this to work?”

👉 Keeps trajectory without breaking trust.

⸻

🔁 The Loop

Anchor → Expand → Bias → Invite → Adjust

Run that repeatedly.

⸻

🧠 What you’re actually doing

Not controlling them.

You’re:
	•	shaping how the situation is seen
	•	which shapes what feels reasonable
	•	which influences what gets chosen

⸻

⚖️ The invariant (don’t lose this)

If the framing only works when hidden, it’s weak.
If it works in the open, it’s strong.

⸻

🎯 Example (quick)

Instead of:

“We should do X”

